$74,901 - $78,793 a yearPOSITION OVERVIEW:
Under the direction of the Manager, Don-Highland, the Project Manager, Don-Highland is responsible for leading, developing and implementing all aspects of watershed projects and related studies including the planning of Authority lands, watershed strategies, community-based regeneration projects, and community engagement initiatives in the Don and Highland watersheds. This position is responsible for leading the development of partnerships and the interaction with partner organizations including all levels of government, consultants, community organizations, and internal and external stakeholder groups. This position leads budget management tasks including the preparation of proposals for non-traditional forms of funding to help achieve watershed objectives. Additionally, this position is responsible for hiring, supervising and evaluating the performance of staff, partners, consultants and contractors. Overall, this position plays an integral role in acting as a resource to ensure the comprehensive implementation of watershed objectives within the Don and Highland watersheds.
RESPONSIBILITIES:
Lead the development, and implementation of watershed programs/projects and community engagement opportunities to support the goals and objectives of TRCA’s Strategic Plan, watershed plans and TRCA’s Community Engagement Strategy;
Develop, design and manage effective locally tailored approaches for the implementation and evaluation of specific projects and programs, including community engagement opportunities;
Develop project charters or project plans and associated business plans;
Coordinate and analyze relevant technical studies, plans and demographic data;
Research leading national and international approaches suitable to TRCA jurisdiction;
Design and guide strategic engagement approaches in response to the local community demographic and interests, with the aim of building shared ownership of the implementation plan and leadership capacity for implementation;
Establish project teams and collaborate with a range of community partners and stakeholders;
Guide, monitor and evaluate projects, and set priorities in consultation with other business units;
Create reports and communications and give presentations and tours to senior staff, Regional Watershed Alliance, and TRCA Board of Directors.
Develop, Implement and evaluate large-scale community engagement events such as Manulife™ Paddle the Don and The Salmon Festival. This involves, but is not limited to:
Developing, managing and implementing project and event logistical plans with relevant partners;
Guiding and managing project team members and event planning committee members to deliver large scale community engagement events;
Working with TRCA’s Communications and Events staff to develop marketing and communication plans and materials for watershed projects, programs and community engagement events;
Ensuring all aspects of health and safety requirements are met;
Managing all aspects of volunteer recruitment and training.
Manage or support TRCA’s community-based committees (such as working groups of Regional Watershed Alliance), stewardship groups and other stakeholder committees;
Support the development and implementation of integrated watershed studies, watershed report cards and other strategies in the Don–Highland watersheds;
Investigate and prepare proposals for non-traditional funding from multiple sources as well as seek sponsorship opportunities in order to support watershed projects and programs;
Develop and maintain successful partnerships and act as a liaison with consultants, municipalities, developers, NGOs, community members, schools, businesses and TRCA staff;
Develop and maintain relationships with current and potential funding partners;
Develop terms of reference and partnership agreements in support of project implementation, comply with required procurement processes and provide ongoing management;
Represent TRCA at internal and external meetings and committees;
Hire, supervise and evaluate TRCA staff, partners, consultants and contractors in order to plan and implement projects, programs and community events. This involves, but is not limited to:
Developing and posting TRCA job postings, interviewing prospective employees, and completing the hiring process in consultation with immediate supervisor and HR staff;
Guiding staff in developing and undertaking annual work plans and professional development plans;
Managing and coordinating work led by various staff, partners, consultants and contractors; and
Conducting annual performance reviews.
Develop and manage program budgets and associated reporting procedures in consultation with the Manager, Don-Highland. This involves, but is not limited to:
Determining staff time, project expenses and contract service allocation;
Adhering to TRCA’s Purchasing Policy during project and program development;
Purchasing supplies required to implement watershed projects, programs and community engagement events; and
Completing quarterly reports, annual summaries and projections for senior TRCA staff approvals.
Prepare and deliver presentations, communications and reports to senior staff, TRCA Board of Directors, member municipalities, stakeholder groups and funding partners;
Act in the absence of the supervisor for specific duties, as required.
QUALIFICATIONS:
Four (4) years of post-secondary education in environmental planning, resource management or related fields.
Minimum five (5) years of experience related to major tasks.
Vulnerable sector screening.
Driver’s license.
 SKILLS AND ABILITIES:
Demonstrated ability to plan, organize and implement projects or programs, manage budgets, and control costs.
Excellent written and verbal communication skills including presentation skills.
Strong analytical and problem solving skills.
Demonstrated knowledge of municipal and provincial legislation relevant to watershed planning including the Planning Act, the Conservation Authorities Act and the Environmental Assessment Act.
Demonstrated ability to work effectively with public organizations, internal stakeholder, volunteer groups and government agencies.
Strong negotiating, influencing and advocacy skills and proven ability to influence outcomes.
Excellent customer service skills and technical expertise.
To apply to this posting, click on the “Apply” icon. Please submit your resume and cover letter quoting job posting # TRCA-089-19 prior to midnight on April 7, 2019.
While TRCA thanks all applicants for their interest, only those under consideration will be contacted for interviews. Please be advised successful incumbent(s) who are not presently permanent TRCA employees may be required to undergo a vulnerable sector and/or driver’s abstract check.
